narratives.question_text: What knowledge, skills, and insights did you develop by taking this course?
comments: We learned different integration strategies and applications of integration.
Feel I have a good grasp on single-variable calculus.
Gained a general understanding of calculus and some derivations for commonly used formulae in math.

narratives.question_text: What are the strengths and weaknesses of this course and how could it be improved?
comments: It is a well organized course with exploration quizzes before each class and concept checks after each class. There are a lot of support systems built into the course, from extra practice sessions to review sessions before each exam. Since there are so many people who take the course, however, information about exams, especially study resources, were poorly communicated, and instruction from TAs was less effective than it probably would have been with the actual professor.
I found the pre-class explorations extremely helpful in helping me understand that day's topic.

The structure of the course is clear and easy to follow using the textbook and doing the problem sets to ensure understanding. The classes were quite long and I believe adding just one class and making the average time per class would be better for learning. The explores were a great tool to think about content before the classes, though it seemed that the professor was not always aware that they were there and that they could connect their content with the explores. A formula sheet per chapter would have been great for better connections of content learned.
I think this course is pretty airtight.

narratives.question_text: Would you recommend this course to another student? Please explain.
comments: I would not take this course unless you have to for major/distributional requirements.
Yes - is a good challenge but also accessible to those who are not in STEM. Helpful for other fields.
It is a great starter course for calculus for those with a basic knowledge of differentiation and integration concepts from high school.
I would recommend this course to any student who is willing to advance their learning in mathematics.

If you thrive in a fast-paced environment, don't mind learning calculus, and could use that credit for your major than this is the course for you. I do not recommend this course to someone who isn't willing to attend office hours or some sort of peer tutoring when they're confused. You will be left behind and the exams will not be kind to you.
